    <prp:abstract>Knowing the mass of the black hole in M87 is necessary to determine if it
is possible for sub-mm VLBI methods to resolve the shadow of the black
hole's event horizon, thereby confirming a basic---yet still
untested---prediction of general relativity.  Despite its importance, the
black hole mass estimates done thus far are discrepant by a factor of
$\sim3$, with methods that use ionized gas favoring a lower, unresolvable
mass and recent stellar dynamical methods favoring a larger, resolvable
mass.  The two methods have used the highest possible spatial resolution
and sensitivity, without hope of better data or analysis for the
foreseeable future.  The only way to resolve this deadlock is with deep,
high spatial-resolution ALMA observations of radio recombination lines
(RRLs) and high density molecular gas tracers.  With the proposed
ALMA observations, we can map the kinematics gas near the black
hole at 0\farcs05 spatial resolution.  With these data, we can conclusively
determine the black hole mass, understand the discrepancy, and finally know
for certain whether the horizon shadow can be resolved</prp:abstract>
